All Things Ephemeral
By Sergei Sazhin/Ralph Rewes</em>
Everything is fleeting. Every length of time changes in our imagination is a slide show.
That boy in sailor outfit — with a shy smile and an inquisitive look — was me. If people

could have guessed my thoughts and see the images that lurked in my mind, they would have found out that fear of losing my loved ones was paramount. I never fantasize with riches. Riches to me were counted in the number of people I loved and the love they returned. That was luxury, the best kind of assets: people, especially my family, my
relatives, my friends. It may not be considered practical in our pragmatic times; but for me it amounted to pure gold coming from life itself, dotted with the brilliant rays of diamonds, pearls, sapphires, rubies and emeralds, cherries, apples, pears and berries.
In my early childhood I especially feared losing my grandfather and my grandmother. I thought then that only old peoples died. I was a kid, yet I stored this fear in my head for 30 years. In fact, I even thought that such fearful thoughts helped them live longer and longer, such fear instilled mental energy in me.

I have this friend in Russia, a friend I would never </em>had but for the fast changes in end of the last century and </em>beginning of this one. We share a lot of things common </em>and a lot of things we do not share. That makes a good </em>friendship: For affinities bind us together and </em>
disagreements make our friendship challenging and </em>interesting. My family dwindles while his is large and </em>grows: I feel jealous when I read him talking about his </em>family affairs, tiffs and tough times included. We shared </em>the fear of the grandparents loss, and a difference, a big </em>difference, I have already lost most of my dear ones.</em>

I had a profound love for rural life. I still do. It was so strong then that sometimes it  became physically painful, like an internal burning flame. It was a tremendous spiritual experience for my soul every time I spent in my village, especially in early summer. I can remember every particularsmell and I found it to be a reflection of Nature. Even now, I still love the aroma of nettle and wild rape plants. The moment one steps out the railway station and into this magic world, one can hold in his breath and drinks the air as if it were pure. unadulterated moon wine.  I can’t help it. Tears of melancholia run from my heart through my eyes. Autumn was the time for bidding farewell. It was the time for the long necked, long legged cranes to dance in courtship, and for the grain to ripe. Every time I had to say good-bye to my village, it felt as if it were the last farewell. Every tree, every turn of road got painfully imprinted in my mind forever. At night, no matter where I find myself in the darkness of midnight, I would always find my way home.

I shared my love and feelings for the countryside, </em>although I spent less time than he did there, only vacations in my father’ s farm. My </em>loneliness lasted 11 years because those were the </em>years it took to welcome my kid brother to this </em>world, and even then the difference of age made </em>me rather a second father than a big brother .</em>

My coming of age came suddenly, together with my first puppy loves. I was infatuated with country girls — a special sort of love: Nightingale's nights and gentle touches,
and befuddled impudence. It is too hard for me to be parted from a girl and not leaving her with a promise or a hope. Every season changed into another.

My coming of age was quite different. I spent most of my time traveling and </em>
moving from one place to another , almost every year a new school, a new city, a new environment and even a new language sometimes. I had my heart ripped apart every time after making some good friends, I could never give myself to anyone for a long period of time. Then your heart carries an emptiness that you know will never ever fill, because time ran out. I had to move on and leave him behind. My personal life was complex to spell it out in a few lines. I dreamed a lot. I observed the world. I wrote everything I experienced. I sometimes cried when I realized how cruel some human being could be, how blind, how careless, how untouched by others’  suffering, but especially I cried out of impotence before the abuse of any defenseless creature, man or animal.</em>

The love for my future wife was the turning ripe. It was mixed with gentleness and jealousy, subtlety and rage. Should my wife love money above all, this story will have never be written. A money loving woman means no free time to dream for a man. She may have
cooled off with time, but I still feel the fire in her. Her job may be more important than husband and son, or is it me acting out jealous?I can’t stand her coworkers and their constant phone calls. I have been on hold every evening. Yet 20 years have passed. Yet, this feeling of mine is still as strong as in the beginning. Perhaps I am too shy to remind her how much I still love her? I begin to understand that my emotions do not make wave on the surface of their souls. I need to live a new, calmer, and quieter life.
I walk away from my dearest,  happiest places because nobody around feels the same. I am really alone and I must learn to think positively. Maybe I am an idiot who cannot find his past.

See? My new Russian friend </em>from season-changing lands did this </em>once; I did it so many times I cannot </em>remember all. I have live in season-</em>changing lands, in lands with no </em>
season where it is always warm. I </em>have in the largest cities, and visited </em>glaciers and deserts. I have enjoyed </em>the most beautiful human smiles and touch, yet to lose them forever after a few </em>days. The smiles my friend encountered have remained with him. He’ s lucky in his </em>own secure way. Yet, he is capable of feeling for those who suffer , and that for sure </em>makes him a great man!</em>
Everything passes: concerns, courtship and even love. Loneliness replaces </em>
them, but maybe it will go away, too. People change with time. Changes is the only </em>
constant. Some of our relatives who claimed love for our motherland sometimes </em>
cannot find the tombs of their parents buried in the weeds. I do not even talk </em>
anymore about traveling in my days off.</em>
August 21, 2007 / April 5, 2008</em>

p.s. My friend Ralph died from diabetes in January 2010.
